%N A395467 Decimal expansion of the area of the constructible squarable lune whose circular arcs have central angles in a 5:1 ratio and common chord of unit length.
%C A395467 One of the five constructible squarable lunes. It was discovered by the Finnish mathematician Martin Johan Wallenius (1731-1773) in 1766.
%C A395467 Called the "hexagon lune" by Shelburne (2005).
%C A395467 See A395465 for details, references and more links.
%H A395467 Amiram Eldar, <a href="/A395467/a395467.png">Illustration</a>.
%H A395467 Mikhail Mikhailovich Postnikov, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2589121">The Problem of Squarable Lunes</a>, The American Mathematical Monthly, Vol. 107, No. 7 (2000), pp. 645-651. Translated from Russian by Abe Shenitzer.
%H A395467 Brian J. Shelburne, <a href="https://bshelburne.wittenberguniversity.org/TheFiveLunes120408.pdf">The Five Quadrable (Squarable) Lunes</a>, Wittenberg University Springfield, 2005.
%H A395467 <a href="/index/Al#algebraic_08">Index entries for algebraic numbers, degree 8</a>.
%F A395467 Equals sqrt((25 + 10*sqrt(5) + sqrt(1325 + 620*sqrt(5)))/2)/10.
%F A395467 Equals f(5*theta) - f(theta), where theta = A395471, and f(x) = x/sin(x)^2 - cot(x)/4.
%F A395467 Minimal polynomial: 50000*x^8 - 25000*x^6 + 125*x^4 - 25*x^2 - 1.
%e A395467 0.7050936871142798360712207004471816530077935442956007...
%t A395467 RealDigits[Sqrt[(25 + 10*Sqrt[5] + Sqrt[1325 + 620*Sqrt[5]])/2]/10, 10, 120][[1]]
%o A395467 (PARI) sqrt((25 + 10*sqrt(5) + sqrt(1325 + 620*sqrt(5)))/2)/10
%Y A395467 Cf. A395465, A395466, A395468, A395469, A395470, A395471, A395472.
